Here's how to implement all three in your `EditProductPage`:

**1 & 2. Intercept back navigation + confirm dialog**

Override `OnBackButtonPressed` in your code-behind:

```csharp
public partial class EditProductPage : ContentPage
{
    private bool _hasUnsavedChanges;

    protected override bool OnBackButtonPressed()
    {
        if (!_hasUnsavedChanges)
            return base.OnBackButtonPressed();

        // Fire-and-forget since the override is synchronous
        Dispatcher.Dispatch(async () =>
        {
            bool leave = await DisplayAlert(
                "Unsaved Changes",
                "You have unsaved changes. Discard and go back?",
                "Discard", "Stay");

            if (leave)
                await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
        });

        return true; // cancel the default navigation
    }
}
```

> **Note:** `OnBackButtonPressed` only fires for the **hardware/Android back button**. For the Shell nav-bar back button, you need `BackButtonBehavior` (below).

**3. Custom "Cancel" back button**

In your XAML, replace the default back arrow with a bound command:

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior
            TextOverride="Cancel"
            Command="{Binding BackCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- page content -->
</ContentPage>
```

Then in your view-model (or code-behind):

```csharp
public ICommand BackCommand { get; }

public EditProductViewModel()
{
    BackCommand = new AsyncRelayCommand(OnBackRequested);
}

private async Task OnBackRequested()
{
    if (!HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
        return;
    }

    bool leave = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
        "Unsaved Changes",
        "You have unsaved changes. Discard and go back?",
        "Discard", "Stay");

    if (leave)
        await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
}
```

**Key points:**
- `BackButtonBehavior.Command` **replaces** the default nav-bar back action, so you must navigate manually (`GoToAsync("..")`) when the user confirms.
- `OnBackButtonPressed` covers the Android/hardware back button separately.
- Set `_hasUnsavedChanges` / `HasUnsavedChanges` whenever a form field changes (e.g., via property setters or `TextChanged` events).
